                     ca. 18. hauing spoken of the manifold Sacrifices of the olde law, and of the Sacrifice of the Crosse, consequently saith, whereby he signifieth, what he vnderstandeth by this sacrifice of bread and wine: I am Christiani peracti eiusdem Sacrificij memoriam celebrant, sacrosancta oblatione, &amp; participatione corporis &amp; sanguinis Christi. The Christians do nowe celebrate the memorie of the Sacrifice of the Crosse past and done, by the holy oblation, and participation of the body and bloude of Christe. So in diuers considerations both these savinges be true, The holy catholike Churche euery where offereth vp to God the sacrifice of bread and wine, and it offereth the Sacrifice of the flesh and bloud of Christe.
               And whereas our daily Sacrifice, which the Christians doo now euery where offer, is the celebration of the memorie of that which was done vpon the Crosse, and therefore oftentimes of the Fathers is named a memorie

or commemoration, as we finde in Eusebius here also alleged by M. Iewel:
